Well, I find shardingsphere handle the XADataSource enlist by themself. see
https://github.com/apache/shardingsphere/blob/12c2f623d5ade73df1a0cb1c6911801c92a8e683/shardingsphere-kernel/shardingsphere-transaction/shardingsphere-transaction-type/shardingsphere-transaction-xa/shardingsphere-transaction-xa-core/src/main/java/org/apache/shardingsphere/transaction/xa/jta/datasource/XATransactionDataSource.java#L77-L100

And there could be a bug on close() method
https://github.com/apache/shardingsphere/blob/12c2f623d5ade73df1a0cb1c6911801c92a8e683/shardingsphere-kernel/shardingsphere-transaction/shardingsphere-transaction-type/shardingsphere-transaction-xa/shardingsphere-transaction-xa-core/src/main/java/org/apache/shardingsphere/transaction/xa/jta/datasource/XATransactionDataSource.java#L103-L109

it should check the current transactio isActive. and if the transaction is active. close method must be defer to invoke after the transation is completion (commit or rollback).

```
void close() {
    if (isActive(transaction)) {
        transation.registerSynchronization(new Synchronization () {
            @Override
             public void afterCompletion(final int status) { this.close(dataSource); }
        }
    } else {
        close(dataSource);
    }
}
```
